    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Beckenham</placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 10<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1882</date>
                    <salute>My dear Farrer.—</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I have just received the enclosed &amp; I think it proper to forward it to you, whether or not you read it.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Will you be so kind as to forward it to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Caird,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> if this appears to you a proper &amp; desirable step.— The badness of the varieties which we raised last year is explained by M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Torbitt’s unfortunate blunder of having used the pollen of a curious, but plainly diseased variety.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>My dear Farrer | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD had enclosed a letter from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4777.xml">James Torbitt</ref>; it has not been found, but see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13608.xml">letter to James Torbitt, 10 January 1882</ref> and n. 2. </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_788.xml">James Caird</ref> had worked with CD and Farrer to obtain financial assistance for Torbitt’s potato experiments.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Torbitt had sent potatoes to CD, Farrer, and Caird in March 1881 (see <hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi> vol. 29, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13083.xml">letter from James Torbitt, 10 March 1881</ref>).</note>
           
        </div>
    
